S3.T3.caption: TABLE III:  Result of applying our method to different upstream models and target datasets.
references:
As shown in Table III, our proposed method achieves performance improvements across all upstream models and target datasets, regardless of language.
Notably, performance gains are observed even on well-performing datasets like EMO-DB, while on underperforming datasets, such as WavLM on EMOVO or XLS-R on CaFE, our method boosts the F1 score by as much as 8 to 11 points.

S4.T4.caption: TABLE IV:  Ablation study with data synthesis and selection process
references:
In this section, we conduct an ablation study using emotion2vec as the upstream model and our default selection criterion (3) to validate each component of our method.
We break down our approach into four key components: training on external data from a high-resource language, translation, translation with expressivity, and bootstrapping data selection process.
As shown in Table IV, all components are necessary for achieving optimal and consistent performance.
Specifically, comparing row 444 and 555, we observe that bootstrapping data selection plays a crucial role in achieving significant performance improvement across all languages.
We also find that bootstrapping consistently improves performance across all ablation settings.
Therefore, results with bootstrapping are presented in row 222 and 333 of the ablation table.

S4.T5.caption: TABLE V:  Experiment to develop guidelines for selecting source dataset
references:
As shown in Table V, we still observe performance gains in 333 out of 444 languages; however, the improvements are less substantial compared to using our default selection criterion.
The advantage of soft labels likely stems from the complex, multidimensional nature of human emotion.
When using criterion (2), false positive data (where the prediction matches its highest-voted class but actually comes from a significantly different distribution) may be selected, leading to diminished performance.
In contrast, selecting based on KL divergence, as in (3), allows us to capture more nuanced differences, such as distinguishing between sadness with happiness versus sadness with anger.
Consequently, we are more likely to select data that aligns better with the distribution of the target dataset Dt​g​tsubscript𝐷𝑡𝑔𝑡D_{tgt}.

In the second experiment, we switch the source dataset from MSP-Podcast to BIIC-Podcast to assess the effect of changing the source language Lssubscript𝐿𝑠L_{s}.
As shown in Table V, using BIIC-Podcast as the source dataset generally leads to performance degradation.
We suspect this may be related to how emotions are expressed and the level of expressivity in different languages.
Previous studies have found that Chinese, for example, tends to be less expressive than English, or that emotions are conveyed through more subtle paralinguistic cues, which are harder to capture [39].
Subtle paralinguistic cues may be difficult for the S2ST to detect and capture.
